; qk-matvec-lane.fk — the quantized matvec with its PER-SUPERBLOCK WORK HOISTED out of the per-weight
; loop, and its row fold carried by a SIMD group instead of a combine pass.
;
; WHY, AND THE MEASUREMENT REDIRECTED THE BRIEF. Stone 5 was sent to fix ACCESS. The standing diagnosis
; was that Q6_K's 210-byte superblock stride (210 = 2*3*5*7, not a power of two) rotates every
; superblock through a different alignment mod 16/32/128, so nothing coalesces, and that a bit-exact
; structure-of-arrays re-layout was the fix. That hypothesis is REFUTED by its own free experiment.
; llama3.2:3b carries the SAME TWO SHAPES in BOTH quants, so alignment can be varied with everything
; else held fixed. Q4_K's superblock is 144 bytes and 16-ALIGNED; Q6_K's is 210 and aligned to nothing.
; Best of 5, M4 Max, off the one resident buffer, one thread per row, serial fold:
;
;   rows x cols     Q4_K (144B, aligned)   Q6_K (210B, misaligned)   ratio
;   1024 x 3072     3.848 ms               0.938 ms                  Q6_K 4.10x FASTER
;   3072 x 8192     6.442 ms               3.466 ms                  Q6_K 1.86x FASTER
;
; The MISALIGNED quant is the faster one, at both sizes. Alignment is not the cost. The cost is per-
; weight ALU, and the contrast says exactly which ALU: q4k_w calls q4k_f16 TWICE per weight (d and
; dmin), q6k_w calls q6k_f16 ONCE — and q*k_f16 calls q*k_pow2, which is a LOOP of up to 15 float
; multiplications. Roughly twice the transcendental work, roughly twice the time. The 2 GB of weights
; move at ~25 GB/s of a ~400 GB/s machine and the arithmetic runs at ~0.7% of f32 peak: this dispatch
; was never bandwidth-bound and never coalescing-bound. It was recomputing a PER-SUPERBLOCK constant
; once per WEIGHT, 256 times over.
;
; Coalescing was measured too, and separately, so the refutation is not an inference. A lane-
; interleaved partition (adjacent lanes read adjacent columns — perfect coalescing) against the
; body's contiguous-chunk partition at the same parts=32, best of 5:
;
;   1024x3072 Q4_K  0.393 -> 0.371 ms      3072x8192 Q4_K  1.150 -> 1.110 ms
;   1024x3072 Q6_K  0.305 -> 0.301 ms      3072x8192 Q6_K  0.855 -> 0.700 ms
;
; 0-18%. Coalescing is worth almost nothing here, which is what an ALU-bound dispatch looks like.
;
; WHAT THIS CELL DOES, in the two pieces the measurement separated, because they have DIFFERENT
; epsilon status and must not be sold as one thing:
;
;   1  THE HOIST — and it needs NO epsilon at all. A thread walking a row visits 256 consecutive
;      weights of one superblock before crossing into the next. d (and Q4_K's dmin) are constants of
;      the superblock. Computing them once per crossing instead of once per weight yields the
;      IDENTICAL f32 value and leaves the association untouched, so the result is BIT-EXACT. Measured
;      against the attestant at parts=1, all rows, six real tensors: worst |d| = 0.000e+00.
;      One thread per row, serial fold, hoisted vs not:
;        1024x3072 Q4_K  3.848 -> 1.103 ms (3.49x)      3072x8192 Q4_K  6.442 -> 2.389 ms (2.70x)
;        1024x3072 Q6_K  0.938 -> 0.935 ms (1.00x)      3072x8192 Q6_K  3.466 -> 2.041 ms (1.70x)
;      Two sizes and a slope, per quant. The free win is largest exactly where the redundant work was
;      largest (Q4_K, two f16 decodes per weight), which is the diagnosis predicting its own size.
;
;   2  THE SIMD-GROUP FOLD — and this one reassociates, so it answers to the named epsilon below.
;      One SIMD group (32 lanes) per row; lane l folds columns l, l+32, l+64, ... k counting DOWN;
;      metal::simd_sum reduces the 32 lane partials. No `part` buffer, no second dispatch, no combine
;      pass. A header-free hoisted split was swept at parts = 1/8/16/32/64/128/256 to see whether it
;      could reach the same place without metal_stdlib. It cannot — it plateaus and simd_sum stays
;      1.4-1.7x below its best point at every shape:
;        3072x8192 Q4_K  best hoisted split 0.509 ms (parts=128)  vs simd  0.435 ms
;        3072x3072 Q4_K  best hoisted split 0.385 ms (parts=64)   vs simd  0.242 ms
;        1024x3072 Q6_K  best hoisted split 0.288 ms (parts=128)  vs simd  0.175 ms
;
; WHAT WAS MEASURED AND REJECTED, and it is the most useful thing this cell learned. llama.cpp's
; ggml-metal kernel_mul_mv_q6_K_f32_impl (MIT; read for SHAPE only, nothing pasted) carries `nr0`
; REGISTER BLOCKING: one SIMD group folds nr0 rows at once so the activation vector is loaded once and
; amortized across nr0 weight rows. It was handed to this stone as the likely biggest term. Built on
; top of the lane kernel below, per-weight arithmetic unchanged, best of 5:
;
;   shape                   simd+hoist   nr0=2    nr0=4    nr0=8
;   1024x3072  Q4_K           0.179      0.196    0.249    0.351
;   3072x3072  Q4_K           0.248      0.258    0.295    0.370
;   3072x8192  Q6_K           0.532      0.555    0.683    0.865
;   128256x3072 Q6_K          5.809      5.838    5.917    6.015
;
; SLOWER at every shape and every nr0, monotonically in nr0. The lever is inert here, and the reason
; is the whole lesson: llama.cpp's inner loop is a handful of bitmask ops, so it is bound by loading
; the ACTIVATION and nr0 amortizes exactly that. This body's inner loop computes the f16 super-scale
; from a LOOP of float multiplications and decomposes the index by division, so it is bound by ALU —
; nr0 amortizes something that was never the cost, and pays for it in register pressure and occupancy.
; A shape borrowed from a kernel with a DIFFERENT BINDING CONSTRAINT transfers nothing. That is why
; the reference was rented for its shape and then re-measured rather than adopted.
;
; WHERE THE REMAINING DISTANCE IS, named and not taken. After this cell, Q6_K 3072x8192 runs 25.2 MMAC
; in 0.532 ms = 47 GMAC/s. An external ollama/llama.cpp oracle on this same machine and model decodes
; at 157.83 tok/s, which at ~3.21 GMAC/token is ~500 GMAC/s — still ~10x above this. That 10x is not
; access and not parallelism: it is that llama.cpp factors d*sc OUT of the inner sum and accumulates in
; QUANTIZED space, decodes with bitmasks instead of division, and vectorizes four sub-lanes as float4.
; All three change the association materially, so all three need an epsilon strictly larger than the
; one below. Named here so the next stone inherits a target and not a mystery.
;
; THE HEADER, AND WHY IT IS NOT THE THING q6k-msl.fk REFUSED. This unit emits `#include <metal_stdlib>`
; — the first Metal unit in the body to do so. It does NOT emit `using namespace metal;` and it calls
; `metal::simd_sum` fully qualified. Both halves of that are load-bearing:
;   * WITHOUT the qualification and WITH `using namespace metal;`, the body's own `round`
;     (ldm-msl-round) becomes AMBIGUOUS against metal_stdlib's and the unit does not compile. Witnessed,
;     not predicted. Qualifying keeps every unqualified name in the unit resolving to the BODY's.
;   * q6k-msl.fk refuses the header so that the f16 super-scale is decoded by the body's ARITHMETIC
;     (fd-value at eb=5, mb=10) and not by `as_type<half>`. That refusal is intact: nothing here decodes
;     a number with a library call. simd_sum is not a numeric recipe the body could own — it is a
;     cross-lane COMMUNICATION instruction, the one thing a scalar language cannot express. That is the
;     line, and it is stated so a later reader can hold this cell to it.
;
; THE NAMED EPSILON, AND WHY THE EXISTING ONE ALREADY COVERS IT. qk-matvec-split.fk derives, for f32
; summation of the same cols products t_j = w_j * x_j under two associations,
;
;     |y_split - y_serial|  <=  (cols + ceil(cols/parts) + parts) * u * SUM|w_j * x_j|,   u = 2^-24
;
; from the fact that an association tree of depth d accumulates at most d * u * SUM|t_j|. This cell's
; tree is a lane chain of depth ceil(cols/32) followed by whatever tree metal::simd_sum uses over 32
; values. Metal does not SPECIFY that tree. It does not have to: ANY association of 32 terms has depth
; at most 31 < 32, so substituting parts = 32 into the bound above is valid for every tree simd_sum
; could possibly be using, including the worst one. The bound is therefore UNCHANGED and needs no new
; derivation — only the observation that an unspecified reduction is still a bounded one. The carrier
; measures the deviation as a fraction of it, per row, every run.
;
; THE ATTESTANT STAYS, UNTOUCHED (corpus row 810). q6k-msl.fk and q4k-msl.fk are not edited by this
; stone — not one character. q6m-matvec-msl / q4m-matvec-msl remain the bit-exact meaning, and this
; cell answers to them at THREE levels every run: the hoisted split at parts=1 is bit-for-bit
; identical to them, the lane kernel stays inside the named epsilon, and the whole path generates the
; same token ids.
;
; THE RADIUS THIS CELL SPEAKS FOR.
;   * The lane kernel assumes a SIMD width of exactly 32 and a threadgroup that is a multiple of 32.
;     That is Apple GPU family 7/8/9 (M1-M4). On any device where threadExecutionWidth != 32 this
;     kernel is WRONG, not slow — the carrier must read threadExecutionWidth and refuse. Stated
;     because a kernel that silently assumes a hardware constant is the aporon error (row 811).
;   * The hoist is bit-exact ONLY because d and dmin are exact functions of the superblock index and
;     the association is untouched. It says nothing about any quant whose per-weight value depends on
;     anything else.
;   * cols >= 1 and rows >= 1. A row shorter than 32 columns leaves the high lanes with nk = 0 and a
;     clean 0.0 contribution — wasteful, not wrong.
;   * Nothing here speaks for f16/bf16 or for any quant other than the Q6_K / Q4_K whose weight
;     decompositions it transcribes.
;   * THE DECOMPOSITION IS TRANSCRIBED, NOT CALLED. q6k_w / q4k_w are monolithic — the invariant is
;     computed inside them and cannot be hoisted from outside — so this cell re-expresses each as an
;     invariant part (*_inv) and a per-weight part (*_wi). That is a SECOND copy of the same
;     decomposition and it can drift. It is held by two independent falsifiers, named below: a band
;     against equireach-gguf.fk's independently-written ewl-flat-at, and the parts=1 bit-exact gate
;     against the untouched attestant at full width on real weights.
;
; Kin: q6k-msl.fk / q4k-msl.fk (q6m-/q4m-matvec-msl — THE ATTESTANT, and the q6k_*/q4k_* helper spine
; these kernels call; they must be emitted into the SAME translation unit), qk-matvec-split.fk (the
; chunk partition, the combine, and the epsilon derivation this cell reuses unchanged),
; equireach-gguf.fk (ewl-flat-at — the independently-written CPU twin the band falsifies against).
;
; preludes: form-stdlib/core.fk form-stdlib/qk-matvec-split.fk
;
; Proven by: form-stdlib/tests/qk-matvec-lane-band.fk (the partition, the cover, the hoist identity
;            and the reassociation) and form/native/metal/metal_first_token.sh (the GPU, the parts=1
;            bit-exactness, the epsilon and the token ids).

(do
    ; ================= the transcription, read back into Form =================

    ; the SIMD width this cell is written for. Named, not spelled inline, so the radius above has a
    ; symbol to point at and the band can state what it is speaking for.
    (defn qml-lanes () 32)

    ; how many weights lane `l` visits in a row of `cols`, and which column its step k lands on.
    ; k counts DOWN in the kernel; the mapping itself is direction-free.
    (defn qml-nk (cols l) (if (ge l cols) 0 (div (add (sub cols l) (sub (qml-lanes) 1)) (qml-lanes))))
    (defn qml-jat (l k) (add l (mul k (qml-lanes))))

    ; THE COVER. Every column of the row is visited by exactly one (lane, step). This is the claim the
    ; band checks by counting — a partition that merely "works" on one width is the aporon error.
    (defn qml-visits (cols l) (qml-nk cols l))
    (defn qml-count-loop (cols l acc)
        (if (ge l (qml-lanes)) acc (qml-count-loop cols (add l 1) (add acc (qml-visits cols l)))))
    (defn qml-cover-count (cols) (qml-count-loop cols 0 0))

    ; the lane-split association, so the band can watch the reassociation actually happen against a
    ; plain right fold on a fixture rather than being told that it does
    (defn qml-lane-fold (xs cols l k acc)
        (if (eq k 0) acc
            (qml-lane-fold xs cols l (sub k 1) (add (nth xs (qml-jat l (sub k 1))) acc))))
    (defn qml-lane-part (xs cols l) (qml-lane-fold xs cols l (qml-nk cols l) 0.0))
    ; the 32 lane partials reduced with l counting DOWN. simd_sum's real tree is unspecified; this is
    ; ONE admissible tree, and the epsilon above is stated to cover every admissible tree, so the band
    ; speaks for the partition and the cover — NOT for simd_sum's association.
    (defn qml-reduce (xs cols l acc)
        (if (eq l 0) acc (qml-reduce xs cols (sub l 1) (add (qml-lane-part xs cols (sub l 1)) acc))))
    (defn qml-lane-sum (xs cols) (qml-reduce xs cols (qml-lanes) 0.0))

    ; the bound's coefficient. It is qms-bound-coeff at parts = 32, unchanged, and that identity is
    ; the whole content of "the existing epsilon already covers this" — the band checks the equality
    ; rather than trusting the paragraph above.
    (defn qml-bound-coeff (cols) (qms-bound-coeff cols (qml-lanes)))

    ; ================= the emitted MSL =================

    ; the header. Emitted ONCE, at the very top of the unit, and WITHOUT `using namespace metal;` —
    ; see the header block: the unqualified `round` the body defines must keep resolving to the body's.
    (defn qml-msl-header () "#include <metal_stdlib>\n")

    ; ---- the hoisted decomposition, per quant: the superblock INVARIANT and the per-weight rest.
    ; Both are float2 for one uniform interface: Q6_K carries (d, unused), Q4_K carries (d, dmin).
    ; Every character below is q6k_w / q4k_w's own body, split at the invariant and nowhere else.
    (defn qml-q6k-split ()
        "static inline float2 q6k_inv(device const uchar* qb, uint b) { return float2(q6k_f16(int(qb[b + 208u]) + 256 * int(qb[b + 209u])), 0.0f); } static inline float q6k_wi(device const uchar* qb, uint b, int i, float2 inv) { int h = i / 128; int wi = i - h * 128; int l = q6k_mod(wi, 32); int g = wi / 32; int is = l / 16; int qlb = int(qb[b + uint(h * 64 + l + q6k_mod(g, 2) * 32)]); int nib = (g / 2 == 0) ? q6k_mod(qlb, 16) : qlb / 16; int qhb = int(qb[b + 128u + uint(h * 32 + l)]); int hi = q6k_mod(qhb / q6k_pow4(g), 4); int q = nib + hi * 16 - 32; int sc = q6k_s8(int(qb[b + 192u + uint(h * 8 + is + 2 * g)])); return (inv.x * float(sc)) * float(q); } ")

    (defn qml-q4k-split ()
        "static inline float2 q4k_inv(device const uchar* qb, uint b) { return float2(q4k_f16(int(qb[b + 0u]) + 256 * int(qb[b + 1u])), q4k_f16(int(qb[b + 2u]) + 256 * int(qb[b + 3u]))); } static inline float q4k_wi(device const uchar* qb, uint b, int i, float2 inv) { int c = i / 64; int within = q4k_mod(i, 64); int hf = within / 32; int l = q4k_mod(within, 32); int j = 2 * c + hf; int qbyte = int(qb[b + 16u + uint(c * 32 + l)]); int nib = (hf == 0) ? q4k_mod(qbyte, 16) : qbyte / 16; return (inv.x * float(q4k_sc(qb, b, j))) * float(nib) - inv.y * float(q4k_mn(qb, b, j)); } ")

    (defn qml-msl-splits () (str_concat (qml-q6k-split) (qml-q4k-split)))

    ; ---- the per-weight inner step, shared by both kernels below. `pfx` is q6k / q4k and `stride` is
    ; that quant's superblock byte stride as a literal. ONE meaning, two quants reaching into it —
    ; the same discipline qms-part-msl keeps.
    (defn qml-step (pfx stride)
        (str_concat "uint idx = r * cols + j; uint blk = idx / 256u; if (blk != curblk) { curblk = blk; b = blk * "
        (str_concat stride
        (str_concat "u; inv = "
        (str_concat pfx
        (str_concat "_inv(qb, b); } float pr = "
        (str_concat pfx
                    "_wi(qb, b, int(idx - blk * 256u), inv) * float(x[j]); acc = pr + acc; }")))))))

    (defn qml-decl () "float acc = 0.0f; uint curblk = 4294967295u; uint b = 0u; float2 inv = float2(0.0f, 0.0f); ")

    ; ---- kernel 1: THE HOISTED SPLIT. Same signature, same partition and same `part` buffer as
    ; qms-part-msl, so it drops into the same combine and the same carrier slot — the ONLY difference
    ; from it is the hoist, which is why parts=1 here is still the attestant BIT FOR BIT. That is the
    ; falsifier for the hoist, and it is why this kernel exists at all rather than only the fast one.
    (defn qml-hoist-msl (fname pfx stride)
        (str_concat "kernel void "
        (str_concat fname
        (str_concat " (device const uchar* qb [[buffer(0)]], device const float* x [[buffer(1)]], device float* part [[buffer(2)]], constant uint& rows [[buffer(3)]], constant uint& cols [[buffer(4)]], constant uint& parts [[buffer(5)]], uint gid [[thread_position_in_grid]]) { if (gid >= rows * parts) return; uint r = gid / parts; uint p = gid - r * parts; uint chunk = (cols + parts - 1u) / parts; uint lo = p * chunk; uint hi = lo + chunk; if (lo > cols) lo = cols; if (hi > cols) hi = cols; "
        (str_concat (qml-decl)
        (str_concat "uint j = hi; while (j > lo) { j -= 1; "
        (str_concat (qml-step pfx stride)
                    " part[gid] = acc; }")))))))

    ; ---- kernel 2: THE LANE KERNEL. One SIMD group per row, lane-interleaved, hoisted, reduced by
    ; metal::simd_sum. Grid is rows * 32 and the threadgroup MUST be a multiple of 32 (radius above).
    ; k counts DOWN so the within-lane fold keeps tb-dot's right-fold direction; only the cross-lane
    ; reduction reassociates, and that is exactly what the named epsilon bounds.
    (defn qml-lane-msl (fname pfx stride)
        (str_concat "kernel void "
        (str_concat fname
        (str_concat " (device const uchar* qb [[buffer(0)]], device const float* x [[buffer(1)]], device float* y [[buffer(2)]], constant uint& rows [[buffer(3)]], constant uint& cols [[buffer(4)]], uint gid [[thread_position_in_grid]], uint lane [[thread_index_in_simdgroup]]) { uint r = gid / 32u; if (r >= rows) return; "
        (str_concat (qml-decl)
        (str_concat "uint nk = (cols > lane) ? ((cols - lane + 31u) / 32u) : 0u; uint k = nk; while (k > 0) { k -= 1; uint j = lane + k * 32u; "
        (str_concat (qml-step pfx stride)
                    " float s = metal::simd_sum(acc); if (lane == 0) y[r] = s; }")))))))

    ; ---- the appendix a carrier adds to the q6k/q4k unit. No helper spine of its own: q6k_mod,
    ; q6k_f16, q4k_sc, q4k_mn and their kin are already defined there, which is exactly why this is an
    ; appendix and not a translation unit. The HEADER, though, must lead the whole file — qml-msl-header
    ; is emitted separately, first, by the cell that assembles the unit.
    (defn qml-msl-appendix ()
        (str_concat (qml-msl-splits)
        (str_concat (qml-hoist-msl "form_q6k_matvec_hoist_f32" "q6k" "210")
        (str_concat (qml-hoist-msl "form_q4k_matvec_hoist_f32" "q4k" "144")
        (str_concat (qml-lane-msl  "form_q6k_matvec_lane_f32"  "q6k" "210")
                    (qml-lane-msl  "form_q4k_matvec_lane_f32"  "q4k" "144"))))))

    0)
